<span id="freeTextContainer9531238722596804695">Lord. This was written in 1988 and I swear it shows the beginnings of Koontz&apos;s obsession with perfect women who somehow become gun-toting quasi military shooters. It&apos;s so odd. The first part of the book was actually really well done and then it just slid sideways into Koontzism and you just wanted it to stop. The ending was nonsensical to the extreme and I just feel irritated for even picking this one to read. I refused to DNF it cause I decided to make sure this book counted for something.<br/><br/>&quot;Ligh</span>
  <span id="freeText9531238722596804695" style="display:none">Lord. This was written in 1988 and I swear it shows the beginnings of Koontz's obsession with perfect women who somehow become gun-toting quasi military shooters. It's so odd. The first part of the book was actually really well done and then it just slid sideways into Koontzism and you just wanted it to stop. The ending was nonsensical to the extreme and I just feel irritated for even picking this one to read. I refused to DNF it cause I decided to make sure this book counted for something.<br /><br />"Lightning" follows the birth and life of Laura Shane. When Laura was born, her mother died giving birth to her during a snowstorm where lightning pierced the sky. Years later, a bad rainstorm with lots of lightning brings a mysterious stranger to Laura's life where she and her father are threatened. Through the years, Laura's "guardian angel" keeps reappearing and the sound of lighting also precedes him. When Laura and her family are targeted she finally meets her guardian and finds out what forces out there mean her and her family harm. <br /><br />I liked the first half of the book following Laura. Though I have to say it gets old real fast when everyone talks about how pretty she is. But the character of Laura is put through a lot of stuff. I thought she was strong and very interesting. I think though after she was no longer a child/teen Koontz didn't know what to do with her. Case in point, we get to see how she meets her husband and I have to say that Koontz needs to stop writing stalking as a prelude to forever true love in his books. I felt turned off by the whole story-line. The book just gets really boring after a while though and I lost all interest in the other characters by the time we have Laura turning into a version of Linda Hamilton a la Terminator. <br /><br />The other characters besides the twins in this one read paper thin. We do get the POVs of the guardian angel character and woo boy I started skimming those sections because they were boring and way too technical/sci fi for me to even care. And when we get to actually have Laura interact with him I went, well gee another stalker. Seriously it's not cute. <br /><br />The writing for part 1 was great and then part 2 just let this book down. The flow was just awful too once we moved on to Laura the adult years. <br /><br />The setting of this book moves from the 1960s through the 1980s and then the 1940s. No spoilers, but honestly when you get to the reveals in this I just rolled my eyes.<br /><br />The ending was double meh. <br /><br />Read on for why this book turned me off so much. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I think what gets me is that anyone else would have blamed their guardian angel for meddling in their lives cause newsflash he is the reason why Laura's husband got shot. He got followed from the past since the person was trying to figure out why Laura was so important. And we find out that Laura really isn't important. A dude from the past decided he fell in love with her after meeting a different version of her in a different future and proceeded to stalk her throughout her life. And then same dude was all yeah I decided to stop helping you from being raped/murdered cause destiny likes a pattern. But you know the version of you I met years ago in a different reality was never raped and murdered so maybe this was destiny deciding I should stop screwing around with timelines. And yes, I love you, but totally could not have prevented your husband from being murdered right before your eyes. I don't even know what to say here. Oh I do. Back to the stacks with you! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I read this book for the "It Was a Dark and Stormy Night" square. </span>
